example.p:
Multipy a^3 times a^2:

        a^3a^2 \amp\amp\amp \text{Represent }a^4\text{ and }a^2\text{ as products}
        (aaa)(aa) \amp\amp\amp \text{Regroup}
        (aaaaa) \amp\amp\amp \text{Represent the product with an exponent}
        a^5\amp\amp\amp\text{Our Solution} \checkmark

subsection.p:
The example shows that a^3 times a^2 just represents 3+2
    a's multiplied together.  Similarly, (a^m)(a^n) just represents (m+n)
    a's multiplied together. This is known as the product rule of exponents:

      \text{Product Rule of Exponents: }
        a^m a^n=a^{m+n}


    Note: In the expression a^n, n is called the exponent and a is called the base.

example.p:
Multiply:

      3^2\cdot 3^6\cdot 3 \amp\amp\amp \text{Same base \((3)\), add the exponents \(2+6+1\)}
      3^9 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

Multiply:

    2x^3 y^5 z \cdot 5x y^2 z^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{Multiply \(2\cdot 5\), add exponents on each of \(x, y\) and \(z\)}
    10x^4 y^7 z^4 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

Divide:

      \dfrac{a^5}{a^2} \amp\amp\amp \text{Expand exponents}
      \dfrac{aaaaa}{aa} \amp\amp\amp \text{Since \(\frac{a}{a} = 1\), each \(a\) in the bottom "cancels" an \(a\) in the top.}
      aaa \amp\amp\amp \text{Convert to exponents}
      a^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

subsection.p:
Because the two a's represented by a^2 cancel two of the five a's represented by a^5, there are 5-2=3 a's left after cancelling.  Thus, dividing a^5 by a^2 just amounts to subtracting the exponents \dfrac{a^5}{a^2} = a^{5-2}= a^3. In a similar way, \dfrac{a^m}{a^n} = a^{m-n}. This is known as the quotient rule of exponents:

   \text{Quotient Rule of Exponents: }
    \frac{a^m}{ a^n} =a^{m-n}

example.p:
Divide:

    \dfrac{7^5 x^8}{7^4 x^3} \amp\amp\amp \text{Subtract the exponents on like bases, \(5-4 = 1\) and \(8-3=5\)}
    7^1x^5 \amp\amp\amp \text{Note that \(7^1 = 7\) since there is only one \(7\) to multiply.}
    7x^5 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

Simplify:

        \dfrac{5a^3 b^5 c^2}{2ab^3 c} \amp\amp\amp \text{Subtract exponents on \(a, b\) and \(c\)}
        \frac{5}{2} a^2 b^2 c\amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

Multiply:

      \left(a^2\right)^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{This means we have three \(a^2\)'s multiplied together}
      a^2 \cdot a^2 \cdot a^2 \amp\amp\amp \text{Each }a^2\text{ represent the produce of two }a\text{'s}
      (aa)(aa)(aa) \amp\amp\amp \text{Three groups of two make six }a\text{'s in all multiplied together}
      a^6 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

subsection.p:
Since three groups of two is 3 \cdot 2 = 6, a quicker method to arrive at the solution is to just multiply the exponents, (a^2)^3 = a^{2\cdot 3} = a^6. This is known as the power of a power rule of exponents:

   \text{Power of a Power Rule of Exponents: }
    (a^m)^n=a^{mn}

example.p:
Multiply:

    (ab)^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{This means we have \((ab)\) three times}
    (ab)(ab)(ab) \amp\amp\amp \text{Regroup the variables}
    (aaa)(bbb) \amp\amp\amp \text{The product of three \(a\)'s and three \(b\)'s can be written with exponents}
    a^3 b^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

assemblage.p:
The Power of a Product Rule only applies to products.  It does not apply to sums for any exponent not equal to 1. For example,

    (1+2)^2 = 3^2 = 9 \amp\amp \text{But,}
    1^2+2^2 = 1+4 = 5 \amp\amp \text{So, }
    (1+2)^2 \neq 1^2+2^2 \amp\amp \text{The rule does not hold for a sum.}


    (a+b)^m\ne a^m+b^m \amp\amp\amp \text{These are NOT equal if \(m\ne 1\), beware of this error!}

example.p:
Divide:

        \left(\frac{a}{b} \right)^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{This means we have the three copies of the fraction multiplied together}
        \left(\frac{a}{b} \right) \left(\frac{a}{b} \right) \left(\frac{a}{b} \right) \amp\amp\amp \text{Regroup the bases}
        \frac{aaa}{bbb} \amp\amp\amp \text{Multiply fractions across the top and bottom}
        \dfrac{a^3}{b^3} \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

subsection.p:
A quicker method to arrive at the solution is to put the exponent on every factor in both the numerator and denominator,
  \left(\frac{a}{b} \right)^3=\frac{a^3}{b^3}. This is known as the
  power of a quotient rule of exponents:

     \text{Power of a Quotient Rule of Exponents: }
      \left(\frac{a}{b} \right)^m=\frac{a^m}{b^m}

example.p:
Simplify.

    (x^3y)^4 \amp\amp\amp \text{Apply the exponent }4\text{ to each factor}
    (x^3)^4 y^4 \amp\amp\amp \text{Multiply powers}
    x^{12} y^4 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

Simplify.

      \left(\dfrac{a^3 b}{c^4 d^5} \right)^2 \amp\amp\amp \text{ }
      \dfrac{(a^3)^2 b^2}{(c^4)^2 (d^5)^2} \amp\amp\amp \text{ }
      \dfrac{a^6 b^2}{c^8d^{10}} \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

Simplify.

            (4x^2 y^5)^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{}
            4^3 (x^2)^3 (y^5)^3 \amp\amp\amp \text{}
            4^3 x^6 y^{15} \amp\amp\amp \text{Evaluate \(4^3=4\cdot 4\cdot 4\)}
            64x^6 y^{15} \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark


\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \underline{\text{First Method}}\amp\amp\amp \text{ } \amp\amp\amp \underline{\text{Second Method}}
\dfrac{a^3}{a^3} \amp\amp\amp \text{Use the Quotient Rule,}\amp\amp\amp \dfrac{a^3}{a^3} \amp\amp\amp \text{Rewrite exponents}
\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{subtract exponents}\amp\amp\amp \text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{as repeated multiplication}
a^0 \amp\amp\amp \text{Method 1 Solution}\amp\amp\amp \dfrac{aaa}{aaa} \amp\amp\amp \text{Cancel out all the \(a\)'s}
\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{ }\amp\amp\amp \frac{1}{1}=1 \amp\amp\amp \text{Method 2 Solution}

When we combine the two solutions we get:

\text{ } \amp\amp\amp a^0=1 \amp\amp\amp \text{ }

Simplify.

      (3x^2)^0 \amp\amp\amp \text{Apply the Zero Power Rule}
      1 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark



\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \underline{\text{First Method}}\amp\amp\amp \text{ } \amp\amp\amp \underline{\text{Second Method}}
\dfrac{a^3}{a^5} \amp\amp\amp \text{Using the Quotient Rule,}\amp\amp\amp \dfrac{a^3}{a^5} \amp\amp\amp \text{Rewrite exponents}
\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{subtract exponents \(3-5=-2\)}\amp\amp\amp \text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{as repeated multiplication}
a^{-2} \amp\amp\amp \text{Method 1 Solution}\amp\amp\amp \dfrac{aaa}{aaaaa} \amp\amp\amp \text{Reduce three \(a\)'s out of top and bottom}
\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{ } \amp\amp\amp \dfrac{1}{aa} \amp\amp\amp \text{Simplify to exponents}
\text{ } \amp\amp\amp \text{ } \amp\amp\amp \dfrac{1}{a^2} \amp\amp\amp \text{Method 2 Solution}

Both expressdions represent the same thing so they must be equal:

\text{} \amp\amp\amp a^{-2}=\dfrac{1}{a^2} \amp\amp\amp \text{}

Simplify.

    \left(\dfrac{5}{3} \right)^{-2} \amp\amp\amp \text{Negative exponents tell us to take the reciprocal}
    \left(\dfrac{3}{5} \right)^2 \amp\amp\amp \text{The reciprocal has a positive exponent, now power rule}
    \dfrac{3^2}{5^2} \amp\amp\amp \text{Evaluate}
    \dfrac{9}{25} \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution}\checkmark

remark.p:
As we said earlier, we want the behavior of our new exponents to be consistent with the behavior of the old (positive-integer) exponents. So we can continue this progression as follows:

      19^1 \amp =19
      19^0 \amp =\frac{19}{19} = 1
      19^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{19}
      19^{-2}  \amp = \frac{\frac{1}{19}}{19} = \frac{1}{19^2}

    \ldots and so on. We arrive at our definitions that anything to the zero power is 1 and negative exponents go to the denominator by simply requiring this progression to be consistent.

subsection.p:
Why is it thatwhen squaring both sides of an equationperfectly good algebra can lead to invalid solutions? The answer is in the redundancy of squaring. Consider the following equation:

                    -5 = 5\text{, is false.}

                    But square both sides, and we get...

                    25 = 25\text{, which is true!}

                    So squaring both sides of a false equation can produce a true equation.
